definition.value: A mononuclear parent hydride consisting of covalently bonded hydrogen and chlorine atoms.
D-Glucopyranose having alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.
An acetylspermidine having the acetyl group at the N1-position.
A L-arginine derivative  having two methyl groups both attached to the primary amino moiety of the guanidino group.
An aminonucleoside antibiotic, derived from the Streptomyces alboniger bacterium, that causes premature chain termination during translation taking place in the ribosome.
A short-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of butyric acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A glycosyl glycoside formed by glucose and fructose units joined by an acetal oxygen bridge from hemiacetal of glucose to the hemiketal of the fructose.
A halide anion formed when chlorine picks up an electron to form an an anion.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from deprotonation of the carboxy group of keto-phenylpyruvic acid.
A butenedioic acid in which the C=C double bond has E geometry. It is an intermediate metabolite in the citric acid cycle.

A glyceride that is glycerol in which any two of the hydroxy groups have been acylated. In the structure shown, two of the R groups (positions not specified) are acyl groups while the remaining R group can be either H or an alkyl group.
An optically active form of glutamine having L-configuration.
A non-proteinogenic alpha-amino acid consisting of cyclopropane having amino and carboxy substituents both at the 1-position.
A dicarboxylic acid monoamide resulting from the formal condensation of one of the carboxy groups of oxalic acid with ammonia.

'Lipids' is a loosely defined term for substances of biological origin that are soluble in nonpolar solvents. They consist of saponifiable lipids, such as glycerides (fats and oils) and phospholipids, as well as nonsaponifiable lipids, principally steroids.
An optically active form of 4-hydroxyproline having L-trans-configuration.
The L-enantiomer of an O-octanoylcarnitine.
An iminium betaine that is the conjugate base of N-methylnicotinic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
An alpha-tocopherol that has R,R,R configuration. The naturally occurring stereoisomer of alpha-tocopherol, it is found particularly in sunflower and olive oils.
A biomacromolecule consisting of large numbers of monosaccharide residues linked glycosidically. This term is commonly used only for those containing more than ten monosaccharide residues.
A tocopherol in which the chroman-6-ol core is substituted by methyl groups at positions 7 and 8. It is found particularly in maize (corn) oil and soya bean (soybean) oils.
An alpha-amino acid that is phenylalanine bearing a hydroxy substituent at position 4 on the phenyl ring.
A penicillin in which the substituent at position 6 of the penam ring is a phenylacetamido group.
The parent compound of the citrulline class consisting of ornithine having a carbamoyl group at the N(5)-position.
A simplest member of the class of isoflavones  that is 4H-chromen-4-one in which the hydrogen at position 3 is replaced by a phenyl group.
An aldopentose, found in the embryos of most edible plants and used in medicine to test for malabsorption by administration in water to the patient.
Catechol in which the hydrogen at position 4 is substituted by a 2-aminoethyl group.
An iron group element atom that has atomic number 26.
An alpha-amino acid that is pentanoic acid bearing two amino substituents at positions 2 and 5.

An iodothyronine compound having iodo substituents at the 3-, 3'- and 5-positions. Although some is produced in the thyroid, most of the 3,3',5-triiodo-L-thyronine in the body is generated by mono-deiodination of L-thyroxine in the peripheral tissues. Its metabolic activity is about 3 to 5 times that of L-thyroxine. The sodium salt is used in the treatment of hypothyroidism.
A beta-alanine derivative that is propionic acid bearing a ureido group at position 3.
A medium-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of dodecanoic acid (lauric acid); major species at pH 7.3.
An oxo monocarboxylic acid that is (3-oxocyclopentyl)acetic acid substituted by a (2Z)-pent-2-en-1-yl group at position 2 of the cyclopentane ring.
The threo-diastereomer of 1,4-dimercaptobutane-2,3-diol.
A quinolinemonocarboxylic acid that is quinoline-2-carboxylic acid substituted by a hydroxy group at C-4.
A cholesterol ester in which the acyl group contains 20 carbons in total and 4 double bonds.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of phenylacetic acid.
The monophosphate ester obtained by condensation of phosphoric acid with the primary hydroxy group of pyridoxal.
A 1-(phosphoribosyl)imidazolecarboxamide that is acadesine in which the hydroxy group at the 5' position has been converted to its monophosphate derivative.
